<ArticleLayout
  title="Garage Shelving: What to Measure Before Buying Storage Units"
  description="Before buying garage shelving, measure shelf depth, height, floor space, load limits, car-door clearance, wall type and the tubs or items you actually need to store."
  category="Garage Storage"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="9 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/garage.webp"
  imageAlt="An organised garage with wall storage, shelves and clear floor space"
>
  <p>
    Garage shelving looks straightforward until the unit is too deep, too tall,
    too light-duty, difficult to access or awkward to position around the car.
  </p>
  <p>
    A storage unit that seems useful online or in a hardware store may not suit the garage
    once you account for door clearance, shelf load ratings, uneven floors, moisture, tubs,
    tools, bikes, cleaning products and the way people move through the space.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying garage shelving, measure more than the wall. Measure how the garage is
    actually used.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide explains what to check before buying freestanding shelves, heavy-duty racks
    or storage units for an Australian garage.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with what the shelves need to hold</h2>
  <p>
    The right shelving depends on what will sit on it.
  </p>
  <p>
    Garage shelves often hold a mix of light, heavy, awkward and potentially hazardous
    items. A shelf used for beach towels and seasonal decorations has different
    requirements from one holding tools, paint tins, hardware, car products or bulk
    household supplies.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying, group the items you expect to store.
  </p>
  <p>Common garage shelving items include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>storage tubs</li>
    <li>camping gear</li>
    <li>Christmas decorations</li>
    <li>tools and hardware</li>
    <li>car cleaning products</li>
    <li>paint tins and renovation leftovers</li>
    <li>gardening supplies</li>
    <li>sports gear</li>
    <li>pet supplies</li>
    <li>bulk household goods</li>
    <li>spare household items</li>
    <li>cleaning products</li>
    <li>small appliances or rarely used household items</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Once you know what the shelves need to hold, you can check whether you need light-duty
    shelving, stronger garage racks, enclosed cabinets, lower storage for heavy items or a
    different storage method entirely.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not choose shelving based only on what fits the wall. Choose it based on the items,
    their weight, how often they are used and whether they need extra care.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure shelf depth before buying</h2>
  <p>
    Shelf depth is one of the most important garage measurements.
  </p>
  <p>
    A deep shelving unit can hold more, but it also takes more floor space. In a narrow
    garage, that can block car doors, walking paths, bins, bikes or access to the house.
  </p>
  <p>Before choosing shelf depth, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>the available floor depth along the wall</li>
    <li>car-door clearance</li>
    <li>walkway clearance</li>
    <li>access to the internal door</li>
    <li>clearance around steps, drains or slopes</li>
    <li>whether tubs will overhang the shelves</li>
    <li>whether items at the back of the shelf will be reachable</li>
    <li>whether the shelves will block power points, taps, switches or meters</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A shelving unit can technically fit and still be the wrong choice.
  </p>
  <p>
    For example, a deep unit along the side wall may leave the car difficult to access. A
    deep unit at the back of the garage may block the path around the vehicle. A deep unit
    near the internal door may make it harder to carry groceries, bags or washing through
    the garage.
  </p>
  <p>
    In many garages, shallower shelves are more useful than deeper shelves because they
    protect access.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure shelf height realistically</h2>
  <p>
    Tall shelving can help use vertical space, but higher is not automatically better.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying a tall shelving unit, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>ceiling height</li>
    <li>garage door track clearance</li>
    <li>roller door or sectional door movement</li>
    <li>lighting position</li>
    <li>power point and switch locations</li>
    <li>whether the unit will be stable</li>
    <li>whether the top shelf can be reached comfortably</li>
    <li>whether heavy items would need to be lifted too high</li>
    <li>whether the unit needs wall fixing</li>
    <li>whether wall fixing is suitable or allowed</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    High shelves are usually better for lighter, rarely used items. Heavy items should
    generally stay lower, where they are easier to lift and less likely to cause injury if
    dropped.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid planning storage that requires awkward reaching, twisting or climbing. If an item
    is used often, it should not live on a shelf that is difficult to reach.
  </p>

  <h2>Check shelf width and bay size</h2>
  <p>
    Garage shelving is often sold in standard widths, but the usable wall space may not be
    standard.
  </p>
  <p>Measure the available width carefully, including:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>door frames</li>
    <li>internal entry doors</li>
    <li>roller door tracks</li>
    <li>pipework</li>
    <li>power points</li>
    <li>taps</li>
    <li>meters</li>
    <li>fuse boxes</li>
    <li>hot water systems</li>
    <li>laundry appliances</li>
    <li>steps or raised edges</li>
    <li>wall protrusions</li>
    <li>skirting or uneven surfaces</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Also check whether a wider unit is practical once loaded.
  </p>
  <p>
    A very wide shelf may hold more, but it can be harder to position, harder to assemble
    and less flexible if your garage layout changes. Two smaller units may sometimes work
    better than one large unit because they can be placed around doors, corners or access
    points.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not block access to essential services. Meters, switches, taps, fuse boxes and
    appliance access points should remain reachable.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure your tubs before buying shelves</h2>
  <p>
    Many garage shelving mistakes happen because tubs and shelves are bought separately.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying shelves, measure the tubs, boxes or containers you already own.
  </p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>tub width</li>
    <li>tub depth</li>
    <li>tub height with lid</li>
    <li>whether handles or lids add extra width</li>
    <li>whether the tubs stack cleanly</li>
    <li>how many tubs fit per shelf</li>
    <li>whether tubs can slide in and out easily</li>
    <li>whether labels remain visible</li>
    <li>whether the tub weight is suitable for the shelf</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A shelf that looks wide enough may not fit two tubs side by side. A shelf may be deep
    enough for the tub base but not the lid or handles. A shelf gap may be too low for a
    lidded tub.
  </p>
  <p>
    It is better to measure the actual containers before choosing the storage unit.
  </p>

  <h2>Check shelf load ratings</h2>
  <p>
    Garage shelving often carries more weight than indoor storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying, check the product's load rating carefully.
  </p>
  <p>Look for:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>maximum load per shelf</li>
    <li>maximum total load for the unit</li>
    <li>whether the rating assumes even weight distribution</li>
    <li>whether the unit must be assembled in a specific way</li>
    <li>whether the unit must be fixed to a wall</li>
    <li>whether the unit requires a level floor</li>
    <li>whether shelves are metal, timber, plastic or particleboard</li>
    <li>whether the material suits garage conditions</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not judge load capacity by appearance alone. A shelf can look sturdy and still have a
    lower rating than expected.
  </p>
  <p>
    Also be careful with heavy items such as paint tins, hardware, tools, car products, bulk
    supplies and boxes of household goods. Their weight can add up quickly.
  </p>
  <p>
    Keep heavy items low and spread weight sensibly according to the manufacturer's
    instructions.
  </p>

  <h2>Check whether the shelving needs wall fixing</h2>
  <p>
    Some shelving units are freestanding. Others may need to be fixed to a wall for
    stability, especially tall or heavy-duty units.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying, check the product instructions and requirements.
  </p>
  <p>Consider:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether wall fixing is required</li>
    <li>whether your wall type suits the fixing method</li>
    <li>whether drilling is allowed if you rent</li>
    <li>whether body corporate approval is needed</li>
    <li>whether the wall may contain services</li>
    <li>whether qualified installation is needed</li>
    <li>whether the shelf will be heavily loaded</li>
    <li>whether children or pets may climb or pull on it</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not assume a freestanding-looking shelf can be used without following the
    manufacturer's installation instructions.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the product requires wall fixing and you cannot or should not drill into the wall,
    choose a different storage option.
  </p>

  <h2>Check the garage floor</h2>
  <p>
    Garage floors are not always flat, clean or dry.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying shelving, inspect the floor where the unit will sit.
  </p>
  <p>Check for:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>slope toward the garage door or drain</li>
    <li>cracks or uneven patches</li>
    <li>raised edges</li>
    <li>damp areas</li>
    <li>water entry</li>
    <li>dust or loose surface material</li>
    <li>floor coatings that may affect stability</li>
    <li>areas where pests enter</li>
    <li>vehicle movement nearby</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A shelf sitting on an uneven or damp floor may not perform the way you expect. Some
    shelving units may need adjustable feet, a level surface or specific placement.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid placing storage where water regularly enters. If the garage is damp, avoid storing
    moisture-sensitive items low or directly on the floor.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan shelf placement around vehicle clearance</h2>
  <p>
    If the garage still needs to fit a car, measure with the car in place.
  </p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>driver's door opening</li>
    <li>passenger door opening</li>
    <li>mirror clearance</li>
    <li>boot or tailgate clearance</li>
    <li>walking space around the car</li>
    <li>garage door movement</li>
    <li>charging cables, if relevant</li>
    <li>access to the internal door</li>
    <li>space for children, pets, prams or bags</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not rely on empty-garage measurements. A shelf may look fine when the car is outside
    but become frustrating once the car is parked.
  </p>
  <p>
    For narrow garages, side-wall shelves need particular care. A back-wall shelf may be
    better in some garages, while a side-wall shelf may work better in others. The right
    answer depends on the car, the door position and the way the garage is used.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep frequently used items at reachable height</h2>
  <p>
    Shelving should make items easier to use, not just easier to stack.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before assigning shelves, think about access frequency.
  </p>
  <p>A practical layout might look like this:</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Shelf zone</th>
        <th>Better for</th>
        <th>Avoid placing here</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Top shelf</td>
        <td>light seasonal items, rarely used decorations</td>
        <td>heavy tubs, chemicals, sharp tools</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Eye to waist height</td>
        <td>frequently used tools, pet items, car cleaning gear</td>
        <td>items that block daily access</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Lower shelves</td>
        <td>heavier tubs, hardware, bulk supplies</td>
        <td>items vulnerable to damp floors</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Floor zone</td>
        <td>large awkward items only if access stays clear</td>
        <td>loose clutter across walkways</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    Frequently used items should be visible and reachable. Seasonal or rarely used items can
    sit higher or further back, as long as access remains practical.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid putting heavy, hazardous or spill-prone items above shoulder height.
  </p>

  <h2>Decide whether open shelves or cabinets make more sense</h2>
  <p>
    Open shelves are not always the best answer.
  </p>
  <p>Open shelving works well for:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>labelled tubs</li>
    <li>bulky seasonal items</li>
    <li>camping gear</li>
    <li>sports gear</li>
    <li>general household overflow</li>
    <li>items that benefit from visibility</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Cabinets may be more suitable for:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>tools</li>
    <li>sharp items</li>
    <li>cleaning products</li>
    <li>chemicals</li>
    <li>items needing doors</li>
    <li>items that should be kept away from children or pets</li>
    <li>dusty garages where contents need more protection</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Cabinets can be useful, but they also need checking for depth, ventilation, locking,
    wall fixing, weight and access.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not use ordinary open shelving for items that need controlled storage.
  </p>

  <h2>Think carefully about chemicals, tools and sharp items</h2>
  <p>
    Garage shelves often become the default place for chemicals, tools and sharp objects.
    These items need more caution than ordinary storage tubs.
  </p>
  <p>Before placing them on shelves, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>product label storage instructions</li>
    <li>whether chemicals need ventilation</li>
    <li>whether products should be kept away from heat</li>
    <li>whether incompatible products need separation</li>
    <li>whether children or pets can reach them</li>
    <li>whether sharp tools should be enclosed</li>
    <li>whether spills could affect lower shelves</li>
    <li>whether the shelf material suits the product</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid storing chemicals above head height or where they could spill onto other items.
    Keep hazardous products controlled and follow label instructions.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you are unsure about storing a product, rely on the label or appropriate expert
    advice rather than a general storage guide.
  </p>

  <h2>Allow space for future sorting</h2>
  <p>
    Garage shelving should not be packed to the edge from day one.
  </p>
  <p>
    Leave some spare space if possible.
  </p>
  <p>A small amount of empty shelf space can help with:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>sorting new items before they become clutter</li>
    <li>rotating seasonal gear</li>
    <li>temporarily placing tools or supplies</li>
    <li>keeping labels visible</li>
    <li>preventing tubs from being wedged in too tightly</li>
    <li>reducing the temptation to stack items awkwardly</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If new shelving is immediately full, the garage may have too much stored in it or the
    wrong categories of items.
  </p>
  <p>
    Shelving helps most when it creates order, not when it simply stores every item that has
    no other home.
  </p>

  <h2>Common garage shelving mistakes</h2>
  <p>Avoid these mistakes before buying:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>buying shelves before sorting the garage</li>
    <li>measuring the wall but not the car-door clearance</li>
    <li>choosing shelves that are too deep for the walkway</li>
    <li>ignoring load ratings</li>
    <li>putting heavy items on high shelves</li>
    <li>buying shelving before measuring existing tubs</li>
    <li>blocking meters, switches, taps or power points</li>
    <li>using shelving on an uneven or damp floor without checking suitability</li>
    <li>assuming wall fixing is optional</li>
    <li>storing chemicals above head height</li>
    <li>choosing open shelves for items that need controlled storage</li>
    <li>filling shelves so tightly that nothing is easy to access</li>
    <li>buying one large unit when two smaller units would suit the garage better</li>
    <li>ignoring rental or body corporate restrictions</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The best shelving is not always the largest or strongest-looking unit. It is the one
    that fits the space, load, access needs and storage risks.
  </p>

  <h2>A simple garage shelving checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying garage shelving, write down:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>available wall width</li>
    <li>maximum shelf depth that still protects access</li>
    <li>ceiling height</li>
    <li>garage door track clearance</li>
    <li>car-door clearance</li>
    <li>walking path clearance</li>
    <li>shelf load requirements</li>
    <li>weight of heavy items</li>
    <li>tub dimensions</li>
    <li>power point, switch, tap and meter locations</li>
    <li>wall type, if wall fixing is required</li>
    <li>floor slope or uneven areas</li>
    <li>damp or pest-prone areas</li>
    <li>items needing lower storage</li>
    <li>items needing controlled storage</li>
    <li>rental or body corporate restrictions</li>
    <li>whether the shelf can be assembled and positioned according to the instructions</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Take these measurements with you when comparing shelving units. It reduces the chance of
    buying a unit that looks right but fails in the actual garage.
  </p>

  <h2>Our take</h2>
  <p>
    Garage shelving should be chosen after measuring depth, clearance and load, not just
    wall length.
  </p>
  <p>
    Start by sorting what needs to be stored. Measure the car-door zone, walking path, shelf
    depth, tub size, ceiling height and load requirements. Keep heavy items low, check
    manufacturer guidance, and be cautious with wall fixing, chemicals, sharp tools and damp
    areas.
  </p>
  <p>
    A good garage shelving setup should make the garage easier to use. If the shelves block
    access, overload the space, hide hazards or make everyday movement harder, they are not
    the right solution.
  </p>
  <p>
    For most households, the best shelving choice is practical, measured and easy to access,
    not simply the biggest unit that fits against the wall.
  </p>

